SIMPLE: wreath
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wreath
<hw>Wreath</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Wreaths</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>wrethe</ets>, AS.
<ets>wr⟦aemac⟧⟦edh⟧</ets> a twisted band, fr. <ets>wr⟦imac⟧⟦edh⟧an</ets>
to twist. See <er>Writhe</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Something twisted, intertwined, or curled; <as>as, a
<ex>wreath</ex> of smoke; a <ex>wreath</ex> of flowers</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>wrethe</xex> of gold.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[He] of his tortuous train⟦br⟧
Curled many a wanton <qex>wreath</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A garland; a chaplet, esp. one given to a
victor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Conquest doth grant⟦br⟧
He dear <qex>wreath</qex> to the Grecian combatant.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Far back in the ages,⟦br⟧
The plow with <qex>wreaths</qex> was crowned.</q>
<rj><qau>Bryant.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>An appendage to the shield, placed
above it, and supporting the crest (see <xex>Illust.</xex> of
<er>Crest</er>). It generally represents a twist of two cords of silk,
one tinctured like the principal metal, the other like the principal
color in the arms.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wreathe</ent>⟦br⟧
